{
  "title": "Class Selectors",
  "cells": [
    {
      "type": "text",
      "data": "<div>In the CSS, a class selector is a name preceded by a full stop (“.”) and an ID selector is a name preceded by a hash character (“#”).\n\nSo the CSS might look something like:<br></div>"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "language": "css",
      "data": "#top {\n    background-color: #ccc;\n    padding: 20px\n}\n\n.intro {\n    color: red;\n    font-weight: bold;\n}"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "data": "<span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: 'Open Sans', 'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px; white-space: normal; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\">The HTML refers to the CSS by using the attributes&nbsp;</span><code style=\"padding-top: 0px; padding-bottom: 0px; list-style: none; float: none; outline: 0px; border: none; font-family: Consolas, Monaco, 'Andale Mono', 'Lucida Console', monospace; color: rgb(204, 0, 0); font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px; white-space: normal;\">id</code><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: 'Open Sans', 'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px; white-space: normal; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\">&nbsp;and&nbsp;</span><code style=\"padding-top: 0px; padding-bottom: 0px; list-style: none; float: none; outline: 0px; border: none; font-family: Consolas, Monaco, 'Andale Mono', 'Lucida Console', monospace; color: rgb(204, 0, 0); font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px; white-space: normal;\">class</code><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: 'Open Sans', 'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px; white-space: normal; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\">. It could look something like this:</span>"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "language": "html",
      "data": "<div id=\"top\">\n\n<h1>Chocolate curry</h1>\n\n<p class=\"intro\">This is my recipe for making curry purely with chocolate</p>\n\n<p class=\"intro\">Mmm mm mmmmm</p>\n\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "data": "<p style=\"margin: 15px 20px; padding: 0px; list-style: none; float: none; outline: 0px; border: none; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: 'Open Sans', 'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px; white-space: normal; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\">The difference between an ID and a class is that an ID can be used to identify one element, whereas a class can be used to identify more than one.</p><p style=\"margin: 15px 20px; padding: 0px; list-style: none; float: none; outline: 0px; border: none; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: 'Open Sans', 'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px; white-space: normal; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\">You can also apply a selector to a specific HTML element by simply stating the HTML selector first, so&nbsp;<code style=\"padding-top: 0px; padding-bottom: 0px; list-style: none; float: none; outline: 0px; border: none; font-family: Consolas, Monaco, 'Andale Mono', 'Lucida Console', monospace; color: rgb(204, 0, 0);\">p.jam { /* whatever */ }</code>&nbsp;will only be applied to&nbsp;<span style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; list-style: none; outline: 0px; border: none; font-weight: bold;\">paragraph</span>&nbsp;elements that have the class “jam”.</p>"
    }
  ]
}